[2]
Date: Mon 31 Oct 2005
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters newsalert, 31 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/T348975.htm>

Bird flu antibodies found at Japan farm
---------------------------------------------
Chickens at a farm near Tokyo have tested positive for an antibody,
indicating that they were infected with a bird flu virus at some time
in the past, Kyodo news agency said on Monday [31 Oct 2005].
The strain of the virus had not been confirmed, but the farm in
Ibaraki, north of Tokyo, will destroy all of its 82 000 chickens, the
agency quoted local government officials as saying.
The farm is inside a zone where a ban had been imposed on the
movement of chickens and eggs because of previous outbreaks of bird
flu, Kyodo quoted the officials as saying.
Japan reported its 1st outbreak of avian flu in 79 years early last
year [2004], when it found chickens infected with the virulent H5N1
strain of the disease.
Ibaraki local government officials had been conducting tests in
preparation for lifting the ban on transferring chickens and eggs
after culling 1.48 million chickens in the area this year [2005], Kyodo said.
